On Sat, 4 Feb 1995, Robert Grimm wrote:

> Thanks for pointing out my omission, i have never heard of Coil so 
> i didn't pay much attention to the fourth member.

They are not very well known. Their most "commercial" release to date has 
been "Love's Secret Domain", the track called "Windowpane" being a bit of 
a hit on the dancefloor - a shame, IMO, as it was one of the weakest Coil 
products ever. I suppose that's why it appealed to the 'masses' - it's 
certainly very much an "easy listening" piece when compared to their 
usual work. 

One other incident of exposure to the public that Coil has had this side 
of the Atlantic was the inclusion of one of their videos into the 
permanent collection of the Museum of Modern Art (the first video 
to be so honoured), after it had been rejected by most video 
distributors as "sick". The video, starring John Balance and Mark Almond,
is overtly a message from the early days of the AIDS crisis; more deeply, 
a symbolic exploration of the figure of Azrael, The Angel of Death, from 
a mid-80s-AIDS-centered perspective. The song is "Tainted Love", a cover of 
Soft Cell.

> Which Jarman movies did the contribute soundbites to? (judging from
> the soundtracks for Last of England, Garden and Edward II they didn't
> to these three movies).

Of course Simon Fisher-Turner  was Jarman's main collaborator; as you 
say, Coil contributed only "soundbites". You will hear them in "The 
Angelic Conversation" and "Blue". There may be more I do not know of.  
There's certainly some theatre-pieces both Jarman and Coil worked on, and 
a painting by Jarman is on the cover of How To Destroy Angels.
(Fwiw, Throbbing Gristle appears in "In the Shadow of the Sun".)

It must be clear by now that I am a great devotee of Coil's, and could 
ramble on for hours. But I realize that even though they are an extremely 
gay-positive group, I am straying from the sort of dicussion proper 
to this forum, so I won't. Actually, they _do_ put me in a very D/s sort 
of space.... But that's a whole 'nother post. Till then let's take this 
to email if anyone's still interested.

As a last little bit of BDSM relevance I'll mention that they wrote the 
soundtrack to "Hellraiser III" :). Unfortunately Clive Barker finally 
decided to reject it because..... it was too "gut-churning". Oh yeah, and 
some of the music on "A Gay Man's Guide to Safer Sex" too...

Orbis, whose name, among many other things, can be translated as Coil.

