I received the message below from Drew RE my recent posts on the absence of
news about and available copies of the new "Servant's Quarters" zine.  What
she says relates to our recent discussion here about s/m publishing: There
*are* publications of significant value to the community that are nonetheless
labors of love or even hobbies for those who put them out, and in these cases
we need to cut a considerable amount of slack.  Much as I, or anyone, might
wish a zine like SG to come out more often, have a larger print run and
better distribution, or meet any other criteria from professional publishing,
under the kind of circumstances Drew describes, we have no right to demand
it.

OTOH (and IMHO, YMMV, and all that stuff), I think we have every right to
expect more from commercial publications that support themselves by selling
us, their customers, to advertisers.  I am just *very* tired of hearing
incompetent or cynically exploitative gay/lesbian publishers make excuses for
years on end -- crying all the way to bank in some cases -- instead of
delivering quality products on schedule and fairly compensating their
artists, photographers, and writers. 

David Stein
