It's different to a very great extent, I'd say; in fact, for those
straight SMers who discover their kink as adults, or for whom their kink
isn't terribly intense, there are more differences than similarities, IMO.
Even kinky heterosexuals mostly don't have the consciousness of a minority
sexuality.  Your average heterosexual doesn't think anything about hir
sexuality, because it's not significant.  It's not made to be significant,
it's not made to be an issue by the culture around us.  Gays and lesbians,
on the other hand, are used to the idea that their sexuality has
implications beyond the bedroom.  I know I see much more consciousness of
this among gay and lesbian SMers, whereas the heterosexuals that I observe
in the scene seem to concern themselves almost exclusively with the thing
itself -- the activity, the sensation, whatever.  Also, I get the feeling
that "stay at home/play at home" is much more prevalent among
heterosexuals.  Gay and lesbian SMers seem to like to socialize with their
kind, and not just to get dates.

