Gayle Rubin wrote:
>A much better museum of medieval and early modern judicial torture can be
>found in Rothenberg, Germany. Rothenberg is a well preserved medieval
>town, and a big tourist destination; it also houses the Museum of Criminal
>Justice.

For anyone planning a trip to Rothenburg, there are two more places to visit
in the vicinity. Regensburg is another well preserved medieval city - though
without Rothenburg's fortifications - and claims Europe's only surviving
original torture chamber. Apparently the other ones were recreated or
re-stocked at a later time. I have no idea if this claim is accurate, but
the town is pretty and worth a visit. 

Nuremberg lies between Rothenburg and Regensburg and has a castle with a
museum and a dungeon.

As for dungeons, my favourite was the oubliette I saw in an Austrian castle.
It was the only one I ever saw that actually had a trap door, just like in
the movies. In case someone is not familiar with the term 'oubliette' it
comes from the French word oublier - to forget - and refers to a narrow
underground shaft or chamber into which someone was dropped and left.

Puts a new spin on 'out of sight, out of mind'.


