On Thu, 27 Apr 1995 Speerhead@aol.com wrote:

> Have y'all seen The Torture Museum in AMSTERDAM?  It'll be the best-spent
> seven guilders when you DO cross their doors.

A much better museum of medieval and early modern judicial torture can be
found in Rothenberg, Germany. Rothenberg is a well preserved medieval
town, and a big tourist destination; it also houses the Museum of Criminal
Justice.  Like the AMsterdam Museum, this one also caters to the tourist
trade. However, it is a much more serious enterprise. The collection is
extensive, well documented, and well displayed. It contains not only
instruments, but also information and documentation of judical torture as
it was practiced in western and central Europe, although the focus of this
particular collection is Germany, which as Peter Boots pointed out, had a
relatively "enlightened" approach. The Rothenberg museum of criminal 
justice has been used as a research collection for serious historical 
work on european systems of "justice." 

"Torture" in this context is a bit misleading, even apart from the
confusion of judicial torture with torture for fun and sexual pleasure. 
There were two different kinds of painful judicial procedures which are
often lumped into the category of "torture." One category consisted of
techniques for questioning suspected criminals or heretics, and for
obtaining confessions of guilt. The second consisted of technologies for
punishing those who were convicted of crime or heresy.  The implements commonly 
seen in such museum "torture" displays are of both kinds. 

Torture as a means of obtaining "truth"  was highly regulated, and in
principle limited the amount of damage that could be inflicted upon a
subject. However, as Peter Boots and others pointed out, judicial torture
was not especially concerned with the physical preservation of its
subjects. While the interrogators were generally supposed to keep their
victims alive until they confessed or were released, they did not hesitate
to inflict severe and lasting bodily harm. Many of the implements used for
questioning inflicted permanent and disabling injuries, for example 
dislocated joints, scars from burning, etc. 

The tortures prescribed as punishment were specifically designed to
inflict serious degradation, extremely severe injury, or excruciating
preludes to painful execution. For example, breaking a person on a wheel
meant binding a person to something like a large wagon wheel, and breaking
all four limbs over the edge. The helpless and disabled person could then
be left on the wheel to slowly die and rot, or could be displayed for a
while and then taken down for further ministrations, such as
disemboweling, burning, or being drawn and quartered. They were not
intended to survive such procedures or emerge unscathed. 

Unlike conventional SM, in these situations was there was little concern
to protect the subject from serious or long term harm. Direct
confrontation with these instruments can overwhelm the capacity of fantasy
to gloss over such messy and inconvenient details. On the other hand, the
alchemy of fantasy often transmutes repugnant thoughts and images into
pleasurable ideas and feelings, and the implements of judical torture can
provide rich raw material for the inspiration of fantasy. These reactions
vary between individuals, or even within individuals. A walk through such 
a museum can provoke a hard one one minute and profound revulsion the
next. 

Many older European (or European-influenced) cities and castles have
displays of similar equipment, although most pale by comparison to the one
in Rothenberg.  For example, Lima Peru has a pretty interesting Museum of
the Inquisition. The Bishop's castle in Salzburg, Austria has a small
dungeon, and some equipment (including an interesting chair fitted with
wooden spikes). There is a lot of hype about the torture chamber at the
Tower of London, but after seeing Rothenberg, the hype was more evident
than the equipment. 

The Museum at Rothenberg has published a couple of books in English which 
show photos of some of the equipment and provide historical and analytic 
material on judicial torture; there is also a book called "Inquisition" 
which is in and out of print, with numerous photographs and illustrations 
of authentic torture equipment. There are now several academic studies of 
torture as a judicial procedure (both licit and illicit) as well. 



