Simply not true.  Much scholarly work has been done on torture, esp.
on less physically damaging methods such as sensory deprivation.
(That pesky old geneva convention, necessity is the mother of
invention and all that...) The US and canadian govts. funded a ton of
academic research done by esteemed psychologist D.O. Hebb at my alma
mater McGill University back during WWII, that according to a PBS
special from a while back now, was being used by the british gov't
against suspected IRA members.  Alas I do not have a reference for
this, or even a title.  Someone on ASB had a better memory than I,
the last time this topic came up, perhaps you might try polling a
wider audience.

I"d be willing to bet that Amnesty International has an extensive
bibliography and if you contacted them in an appropriately academiic
manner they'd point you at some legit sources of info.  "I'm trying to
plan a really cool mindfuck torture scene for my new slave" wouldn't
be the way I personally would approach them...


