In a recent post on "Forced Feeding," Des de Moor 
(dirkje@dircon.co.uk) asked about the technique of forced feeding
used on people involved in hunger strikes, etc.
 
Following is a description of a technique which can be used to
provide food and rehydration for people who may (for some unknown
reason) be restrained and involved in activities which render them
helpless to feed themselves---or helpless to reject food or liquid
provided by a generous and concerned top. (For example, if a
person were for some reason to be restrained, have a catheter
installed to prevent control of urinary functions, a Bardex enema
nozzle to flush his bowels periodically and without his consent or
control, periodic genital stimulation to prevent orgasm control,
periodic breathing restriction....well, you get the idea.)
 
If you get queasy, don't read the rest. The technique:
 
The required equipment is a long Levin tube or stomach tube, or
even a very long feeding catheter. The top should (not too subtly)
hold the tube up and use it to measure the approximate distance
from the bottom's nose to his stomach (use the navel as an approx-
imate guide); that's how much you'll insert. The bottom is invited
to recline, the catheter is *liberally* lubricated with plain KY
(not the type with Nonoxynol-9 added), and it is slowly inserted
up one nostril. It will go into the throat without difficulty.
(Some bottoms will at this point have a passing "gag" reflex. This
can be suppressed--and the entire procedure facilitated--by having
the bottom swallow repeatedly; remind him frequently.)
 
When the appropriate length of the tube has been inserted the
bottom will feel no particular pain, although there may be some
minor discomfort because some people just aren't used to having
something go into their nose and down the throat; that discomfort
will pass.
 
Be sure that the bottom's mouth is unobstructed during this
procedure; no gag or other restriction should be used. Besides,
you want the bottom to be able to tell you what he's feeling and
experiencing. Stroking the bottom's cock lightly while you insert
the tube will sometimes take the bottom's mind off any discomfort
and relieve any fear or anxiety.
 
THIS STEP IS IMPORTANT: Lightly clamp off the bottom's OTHER
nostril and make him shut his mouth and EXHALE. Place your ear
immediately next to the distal end of the tube; you should hear or
feel NO air coming from the tube. There may be some leakage of air
around the tube, but it will come from the nostril in which the
tube is inserted, not from the tube itself. If you hear a flow of
air from the tube, you have inadvertently inserted the tube into
his lung rather than his stomach; the tube must be removed and re-
inserted. You don't want to fill up his lung with fluid.
 
To provide food or rehydration via this tube, a large catheter-tip
syringe is helpful; the 60cc type used to withdraw urine from a
urethral catheter is ideal. Simply fill the syringe with liquid
food such as "Ensure" or with water, and send it down the tube to
the bottom's stomach.  
 
Monitor the bottom's urine output if the scene is a long one; be
sure he gets enough fluid  to make up for fluid lost through the
bladder. When removing the tube, simply pull it out slowly and
gently, and immediately allow the bottom to blow his nose to
remove any residual lubricant so it doesn't drip back down his
throat.
 
CAUTIONS: This is a fairly sophisticated type of control scene.
Monitor the bottom's ability to breathe constantly; do not attempt
this kind of scene if the bottom is suffering from a cold or from
any illness which restricts normal breathing through the nostril
you're not using. If the bottom should get into a coughing fit,
it's best to remove the tube. Be sure the tube used is suited to
this purpose; it should have a smooth tip so as not to irritate
the nasal and esophageal passages and ideally a side "eye" to
avoid problems of clogging from mucous. Needless to say, it is
possible there could be transfer of germs from the tube to the
bottom, so it should be sterilized before use; ordinary bacteria
in the air are not so much of a concern as those special pathogens
which are transmitted from person to person directly or via
contaminated equipment.
 
I hope the women reading this posting will not be offended by the
use of the words him/his above. I don't mean to be "un-inclusive;"
I am writing from my own experience. I'm sure our female readers
can adapt both the technique and the language to their own needs.

Tom
(tagordon@prairienet.org)

