Welcome to the gl-asb mailing list!

Please save this message for future reference.  Thank you.

If you ever want to remove yourself from this mailing list,
you can send mail to <Majordomo@QueerNet.ORG> with the following
command in the body of your email message:

    unsubscribe gl-asb eb85131@goodnet.com

If you ever need to get in contact with the owner of the list,
(if you have trouble unsubscribing, or have questions about the
list itself) send email to <owner-gl-asb@QueerNet.ORG> .
This is the general rule for most mailing lists when you need
to contact a human.

 Here's the general information for the list you've subscribed to,
 in case you don't already have it:

[Last updated on: Sat Jan 11  8:18:53 1997]
The GL-ASB and GL-ASB-DIGEST mailing lists
==========================================
This fairly long message outlines the policies and procedures for these
mailing lists.  Please read it thoroughly, and save it for future 
reference.


Section 1:
What is it?  Who can subscribe?  What may be posted?
----------------------------------------------------

I.	What is "gl-asb"?

"gl-asb" is a mailing list for discussion of B&D/D&S/S&M interests and
practices involving same-sex partners.

II.	Why does this require separate space?

Many of the folks involved in the establishment of this list were
subscribers to the Usenet newsgroup "alt.sex.bondage"; hence the
historical "asb" in its name.  

Some of us at the time felt that our presence on alt.sex.bondage was
limited by some or all of the following factors:

- Some other people were uncomfortable with same-sex postings, and
  seemed to post back with extra ferocity and volume every time a
  same-sex interest was posted, attempting to drown it out

- Some people would attack our assertions that we derived some special
  sort of energy from same-sex interactions, saying things like
  "genitalia are just another sort of drag -- some day you'll mature
  to the point that you can get over silly hangups like the gender of
  your partner" and the like

- Even when neither of these were the case, some of us felt that the
  fair and typical distribution of volume among same-sex and different-sex
  interests resulted in our losing focus

Therefore, this list was set up to provide a forum in which people could
focus on specifically same-sex topics.

III.	Who is welcome to subscribe?  Who is welcome to post?

Despite the fact that the "gl" in the list name stands for "gay and
lesbian," subscription and posting provileges are not restricted to
people who identify as gay or lesbian.  People of all genders and 
orientations are welcome to subscribe.  The restriction on this list 
is one of subject matter, not membership.

People of all genders and orientations are welcome to post as well.
But remember that the topic of this list is *same-sex* interactions.
If you have a general point to make in a discussion of same-sex
topics, fine; but remember that there are many other spaces on the
Internet to discuss B&D/D&S/S&M in general, or interactions involving
different-sex participants.  Proclamations of your heterosexuality,
dropping your opposite-sex partners into discussion or examples, and
the like tend to cause the list to lose its focus.  If you're not
prepared to keep the discussion in a same-sex context, you might
consider whether other forums, like alt.sex.bondage or the THYST-L
mailing list (which has a more multi-orientational flavor, and is
especially suitable for people participating in actively bisexual
B&D/D&S/S&M arrangements), might not be more suitable to your tastes
and needs.

IV.	If people other than gay men and lesbians are welcome
	here, why the "gl" in the name?

It seemed like a good idea at the time, and once a list is set up
these days, information about it tends to be available in so many
slow-to-change media (like books and on-line indices) that changing
names is difficult.  Our list management software is expected to
be enhanced to allow lists to have aliases; when this is done, we will
probably change the name to something more appropriate to the charter.

V.	Why limit yourself?  What about the diversity of human
	experience?  Don't we all benefit from sharing in the broad
	range of human histories and influences?

Sure we do.  But not here.  As I said, we've experienced the down
side of being drowned out by a diverse environment.


Section 2:
How do I subscribe, unsubscribe, change formats, or retrieve
files and back issues?
------------------------------------------------------------

I.	What formats is the list available in?

gl-asb is available as a "reflector" list, where each message posted
to the list shows up as a separate message in your mailbox, or as a
"digest," where separate messages are batched up into one or two
mail bundles a day.

The Majordomo software we use to administer our lists actually
keeps track of these as two separate mailing lists, the former
called "gl-asb" and the latter "gl-asb-digest".

II.	How do I subscribe?

You subscribe by sending a mail message to

	majordomo@queernet.org

In the body of the message, you put a command, a line of specific
words in a specific format.  (Majordomo isn't a very bright software
package, but it makes our job a lot easier; you need to be very
careful about the format of the commands.)

If you wish to receive the reflector format, and have it delivered
to the address you sent the request from, put the line

	subscribe gl-asb

in the body of the message.  For the digest format, use the command

	subscribe gl-asb-digest

instead.

If you wish to specify an address other than the one that's automatically
taken from your mail's "From:" or "Reply-To:" headers (because the headers
are incorrect, or you're subscribing or unsubscribing an address on a
specific system), put the address at the end of the command line:

	subscribe gl-asb imkinky@bdsm.com

for example.

III.	How do I unsubscribe?

To unsubscribe, you also send a command to majordomo@queernet.org;
it would be

	unsubscribe gl-asb

or

	unsubscribe gl-asb-digest

depending on the list you're on.  Please note that sometimes your 
administrator changes your address, or the routing to it, without
your being aware of it, so you may need to specify the address in
the command like this:

	unsubscribe gl-asb imkinky@bdsm.com

The exact command you need is in your WELCOME message.

IV.	How do I switch from reflector to digest, or from digest
	to reflector?

Since Majordomo treats them as two separate lists, you need to
unsubscribe from the old format, and subscribe to the new format.
You can do this on multiple command lines in the same mail message:

	To: majordomo@queernet.org
	Subject: Doesn't matter

	unsubscribe gl-asb
	subscribe gl-asb-digest

V.	How much mail will I get?

On the average, gl-asb tends to have about five to 20 posts a day, in one
or two digests.

However, when you first subscribe, our mailer does you a "favor": it
sends you all queued mail, which is up to seven days' worth.  Don't
worry: after the initial burst, traffic stabilizes.

VI.	I just got mail telling me my request needs to be "approved".
	Why, and how long does this take?

Some of our lists have been subjected to harrassment by people who
send "die fags" mail to the lists.  (Thank you, Westboro Baptist
Church.)  In order to prevent this, we restrict permission so that
only subscribers can post.  We further have "closed" the subscription
process so we might screen out requests from known harrassers.  If
you've never harrassment-bombed us, your request will be approved --
there's no need to enclose your resume (although if the 8x10 glossies
are e-mailable, that might accelerate the process... only kidding,
but you can't blame a list administrator for trying).

While we normally approve requests on the same day, if the person who
needs to handle the request is traveling, you might face a several-day
delay.

VII.	How do I send mail to the list?

All mail to be distributed to all list members should go to 

     gl-asb@queernet.org

Be careful, in particular, when replying to mail received from the
list.  While most Macintosh, UNIX, and MS-DOS/Windows mail programs
handle the headers we supply correctly, and send mail back to the
entire list if you ask it to reply to all addressees (and allow you
to send a response to the original poster only, as well... more
on that later).  But some on-line services and BBS systems send
send replies to the incorrect address; you'll need to be sure it's
correct before you send it.  (This can be simplified by putting our
address in your alias list or address book or whatever your software
calls it.)

Note that your mail to addresses like "owner-gl-asb@queernet.org"
does NOT go to the list.  It only goes to me, and I may be able to
return it to you for correct addressing, but thar may be delayed 
as well.

VIII.	When should I send a reply to the list?  When should I send
	it to the original poster only?

Ask yourself if the other 500+ people on the list really want to
hear it.  (Then ask a second time.)  If you really just want to
send a personal note to the other party, please do so.

IX.	I sent mail to the list, a day or so has passed, and it
	hasn't appeared in my mailbox or in the digest.  Why?

One reason this can happen is that you may have posted from a
different system, or from a different AOL screen-name, or from a
system where the headers have changed since you subscribed, or from
a new host where your mail is forwarded to.  We try to find these
and tell you about them, but we can't always do so (or figure out
who you really are).

X.	Other than opposite-sex stuff, what shouldn't I post to
	the list?

For starters, anything that isn't about B&D/D&S/S&M, no matter how
tempting or important you think it is.  For example, many of our lists
recently received a lot of "Internet Virus" warnings.  Not only were
these not true and a big waste of bandwidth, but when one of these
situations really occurs, you'll probably be notified about it BY YOUR 
PROVIDER.

Announcements of publications or events that are B&D/D&S/S&M related
but may not have exclusively a same-sex nature, such as toy fairs, etc.
are welcome, but try to keep them short and devoid of opposite-sex-
specific content as well.  (This doesn't mean that you should lie
about or omit mention of celebs involved who are bi- or hetero-
identified.  But use a little common sense and sensitivity in 
applying this guideline.)

Personal ads are inappropriate for the list; they change the tone of
the list so that, over time, it becomes a pickup space and not much
more.  We have a weekly distribution of ads to the list, however, in
order to allow people to get in contact without changing the tone of
the discussion list.  Send personal ads to "gl-asb-personals@queernet.org".

Next, anything that's an ad hominem attack raises the "temperature" of
any discussion without adding any content.  If you wish to insult
someone, please take it to private e-mail.

Finally, if someone is posting off-topic or otherwise inappropriately,
the temptation to respond on the list can be very strong, but it mainly
has the same effect as the original inappropriate posting.  Notify the
list management at "owner-gl-asb@queernet.org" about the issue instead.

XI.	How do I retrieve back issues of gl-asb from the archive?

You cannot retrieve individual posts at present, or search for messages
about specific subjects.  You can, however, retrieve specific issues
of the digest (whether you are a digest or reflector subscriber).

Each issue has a name of the format

	vXX.nYYY

where XX is replaced by the two-digit volume number (we are in volume
02 now), and YYY by the three-digit issue number.

For example, to retrieve Volume 1, Issue 12, subscribers to the
reflector format would put this line in the body of their mail to
majordomo@queernet.org:

	get gl-asb v01.n012

Digest subscribers would say

	get gl-asb-digest v01.n012

X.	How do I find out what's in the archive?

Send this command to majordomo@queernet.org:

	index gl-asb

or

	index gl-asb-digest

(Right now, we only have back issues.  But this could change.)

========================================================================

Enjoy your participation in the gl-asb list!

If you have any questions, drop a note to

	gl-asb-approval@queernet.org


